`crates/ctx-context/src` is the read-side CTX tool: given a repo path, it computes and serves the chain of rollup/intent/leaf context documents an agent should read before touching that path, either as a one-shot CLI print or as a Claude Code `PostToolUse` hook injection. Depending on this crate gets you two entry points — `cli::dispatch` and `hook::run` — both of which are fail-open and never panic on bad input; everything downstream of them shares that guarantee.

The core pipeline is `repo_path` (validates untrusted path strings) → `chain` (maps a validated path to an ordered list of rollup/intent/leaf node paths) → `serve` (reads those paths through `env::Env`, substitutes absence markers, tags freshness via `freshness::assess`, and renders `=== id [kind] ===` sections) → `session` (dedups already-served node ids per session so hook and CLI-path mode never redundantly re-show the same node). Changing the chain's node ordering, `NodeKind::label()` values, or the `render` section format requires updating all downstream consumers of rendered/served output together — these are the tightest cross-file couplings in the subtree.

`env::Env` is the sole I/O boundary; `serve`, `freshness`, `session`, and `hook` all take it as an abstraction rather than touching `std::fs`/`std::env` directly, which is what makes them testable with fakes. `error::CtxError` is the single error type everything returns — no `Box<dyn Error>` anywhere. `cli.rs` and `main.rs` split argv/stdin/exit-code wiring from dispatch logic; `cli::CONTRACT` is a doc-synced constant that must stay matched with `CLAUDE.md`/`README.md`. `hook.rs` and `serve.rs` jointly own the session-dedup contract via `session::ENV_SESSION_ID`/`session::load`/`save` — both must agree on the ledger's node-id semantics.

Invariant spanning the subtree: nothing here writes source or generated `.ctx`/`rollup.ctx` content — it's strictly read/serve/inject, matching the crate doc's "read-only tooling" framing in `lib.rs`.